 John Milton, McEleney explores the ambivalence these writers display toward literature’s potential for useless, frivolous vanity. Tracing that ambivalence forward to the modern era, this book also shows how contemporary critics have recapitulated Renaissance humanist ideals about aesthetic value. Against a longstanding tradition that defensively advocates for the redemptive utility of literature, Futile Pleasures both theorizes and performs the queer pleasures of futility. Without ever losing sight of the costs of those pleasures, McEleney argues that playing with futility may be one way of moving beyond the impasses that modern humanists, like their early modern counterparts, have always faced.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aEnglish literatureyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature and societyzEnglandxHistoryy16th century. 0aLiterature and societyzEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aPleasure in literature. 0aSenses and sensation in literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh  aRenaissance Literature.  adeconstruction.  afutility.  apleasure.  aqueer theory.  aromance.  avanity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311072901640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082327268640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823272686423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823272686.jpg  a978-3-11-072901-6  Fordham University Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK